So sorry for the long radio silence, but we have been very busy over the Holidays. Like last year at the same time, we have had a large number of Flying Foxes come into care due to paralysis syndrome. These guys are incredibly weak and many require intensive care. The cause is still unknown but investigations into environmental toxins are ongoing. There are many similarities to the Lorikeet Paralysis Syndrome which is also under active investigation.

Caribbean white tent-making bats look like cotton wool balls. They have entirely white fur, which is only found in six of the 1,300 known species of bat. They construct “tents” out of Heliconia leaves by strategically cutting the leaf ribs with their teeth; they roosts in tents during the day. These vegetarians live almost exclusively on figs and the yellow noses and ears are thanks to the carotenoids in their diet. Female bats choose to mate with males with the yellowest noses, which are though to indicate overall good health.
